When the Tower hearings opened, all manner of accusations came to public notice.
At his hotel, Mr. Tower was accorded that doubtful tribute to instant-celebrity status, the media stakeout.
None of the charges, at least on Mr. Tower's showing, proved to have the least substance.
No use.
Most Democrats, in the end, went with Sen. Nunn.
Sen. Nunn had every reason to know that the moral and ethical charges leveled at Mr. Tower, and investigated exhaustively by the FBI, were flimsy.
"Tower, you were lynched," Mike Wallace, the CBS correspondent, told him.
Worse yet, the lynch mob remains at large.
